'''Kota Shrine'' (Kota Jinja) is a shrine located in Gochi, {{ill|lt=Niigata Prefecture|Q132705|qid=Q132705|1=Niigata Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Joetsu City|Q582289|qid=Q582289|1=Jōetsu, Niigata}}. {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, {{ill|lt=Echigo Province|Q666514|qid=Q666514|1=Echigo Province}}{{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|qid=Q1656379|1=Ichinomiya}}, and {{ill|lt=modern company rank system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=old company rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=prefectural company|1=UNKNOWN}}.

=== Company name ===
The company name ``Ita'' is an old notation that can be found in various documents including ``{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}'' and {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}. Regarding Kun, it appears to be ``keta'' in the ``Jingishiryo'', ``eta'' in the Kujo family book, Takeda family book, and Yoshida family book, and ``kota'' in ``{{ill|lt=Jinmyocho kosho|Q11588824|qid=Q11588824|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō Studies}}'', but it is currently read as ``kota'' {{Sfn|Etsusa Shrine|2002|p=14-15}}. Keta Shrine located along the coast of the Sea of Japan (Disambiguation)|Q11548075|Keta Shrine}} It is said that it was called ``Keta'' in ancient times, and it is thought that it was not called ``Kota'' or ``Ita'' until later times.

In addition, there is an ancient example of reading ``ke'' as ``ke'' on a {{ill|lt=kin-inscribed iron sword|UNKNOWN|lt=iron sword excavated from the Inariyama Tumulus}} dating back to the end of the 5th century {{Sfn|Ichinomiya system in medieval countries|2000|p=368-369}}.

=== Enshrined God ===
The following four deities are currently enshrined. group="Note">In the explanation board in the precincts, the enshrined deities are listed as 3 deities: Okuninushi no Mikoto, Nunagawahime no Mikoto, and Takeminakata no Mikoto, and in the shrine statement book of 1883, they are listed as 3 deities: Ōkuninushi no Mikoto, Nunagawa Hime no Mikoto, and Jishironushi no Mikoto. {{Harv|Ichinomiya system in medieval countries|2000|p=368-369}}. </ref>. 
* {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Ōkuninushi|1=Ōkuninushi}} (Ookuninushi no Kami)
* {{ill|lt=Numagawa Hime|Q11142832|qid=Q11142832|lt=Nunagawa Hime-kami|1=Nunakawahime}} (Nunagawa Himenokami) - Also known as ``Numakawa Hime'' in literature. Wife of Okuninushi.
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q9150391|lt=Takeminakata no kami|1=Takeminakata}} (Takeminakata no kami) - Son of Okuninushi no kami.
* {{ill|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi|Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi no Kami|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}} (Kotoshironushi Mikami) - Son of Okuninushi.

=== History ===

=== Founding ===
